mes New Roman";  mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi;} </style> <![endif]--> <p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-top: 6.0pt; line-height: 115%;"><span style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: &quot;Verdana&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-GB">DIVERSITAS was the International Program of Biodiversity Science that was integrated in Future Earth in 2014. In 2013-2014, the NSF Grant 0839981 supported a number of scientific DIVERSITAS activities and core projects that contributed to improved predictions of climate change impact on biodiversity and that were of direct relevance to the IPCC and IPBES work. In particular, these activities contributed to the harmonisation of biodiversity models used for biodiversity scenario and to the development of models and scenarios associating biodiversity changes. Furthermore, an international network on rapid evolution to climate change was built. </span></p> <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 115%;"><span style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: &quot;Verdana&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;" lang="EN-GB">The NSF grant also supported a number of DIVERSITAS activities that contributed to building a Global Biodiversity Observing System (GEO BON), which led the development of <span style="color: black; mso-bidi-font-weight: bold;">a set of Essential Biodiversity Variables (EBVs), akin to the GCOS Essential Climate Variables (ECVs).</span></span></p> <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 115%;"><span style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: &quot;Verdana&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: black; mso-bidi-font-weight: bold;" lang="EN-GB">A series of DIVERSITAS science-policy activities were also supported by NSF during this period. This includes contribution to the international assessments such as IPBES and IPCC and to the work of the Conventions (</span><span style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: &quot;Verdana&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; mso-bidi-font-family: Verdana;" lang="EN-GB">the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) and the UN </span><span style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: &quot;Verdana&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: black; mso-bidi-font-weight: bold;" lang="EN-GB">Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC). In particular, DIVERSITAS contributed to the development of the 4th Global Biodiversity Outlook (GBO-4), and to the CBD work on indicators and monitoring and on Access and Benefit-Sharing (ABS). As a result, two ABS documents were published: 1) <a href="http://www.icsu.org/latin-america-caribbean/publications/policy-briefs/implementing-access-benefit-sharing-abs/implementingaccess-benefit-sharing">Implementing Access &amp; Benefit-Sharing &amp; Ensuring Academic Non-Commercial Research for the Conservation &amp; Sustainable Use of Biodiversity</a> and 2) <span class="kssattr-macro-textarea-field-view"><span style="background: white;"><a href="https://portal.fiocruz.br/sites/portal.fiocruz.br/files/documentos/abs-brochure_eng.pdf">Access and Benefit-Sharing in Latin America and the Caribbean: A science-policy dialogue for academic research</a>. Overall, over 70 publications were produced as a result of DIVERSITAS activities in 2013-2014.</span></span></span></p> </p><br> <p>            Last Modified: 12/16/2016<br>      Modified by: Deliang&nbsp;Chen</p> </div> <div class="porSideCol"></div> </div>]]></DRECONTENT>
<POR_COPY_TXT><![CDATA[   12.00      Normal 0   21   false false false  FR X-NONE X-NONE              MicrosoftInternetExplorer4                                                                                                                                                                table.MsoNormalTable  {mso-style-name:"Table Normal";  mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;  mso-tstyle-colband-size:0;  mso-style-noshow:yes;  mso-style-priority:99;  mso-style-qformat:yes;  mso-style-parent:";  mso-padding-alt:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt;  mso-para-margin:0cm;  mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt;  mso-pagination:widow-orphan;  font-size:11.0pt;  font-family:"Calibri","sans-serif";  mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;  mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;  mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman";  mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast;  mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri;  mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;  mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman";  mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi;}   DIVERSITAS was the International Program of Biodiversity Science that was integrated in Future Earth in 2014. In 2013-2014, the NSF Grant 0839981 supported a number of scientific DIVERSITAS activities and core projects that contributed to improved predictions of climate change impact on biodiversity and that were of direct relevance to the IPCC and IPBES work. In particular, these activities contributed to the harmonisation of biodiversity models used for biodiversity scenario and to the development of models and scenarios associating biodiversity changes. Furthermore, an international network on rapid evolution to climate change was built.  The NSF grant also supported a number of DIVERSITAS activities that contributed to building a Global Biodiversity Observing System (GEO BON), which led the development of a set of Essential Biodiversity Variables (EBVs), akin to the GCOS Essential Climate Variables (ECVs). A series of DIVERSITAS science-policy activities were also supported by NSF during this period. This includes contribution to the international assessments such as IPBES and IPCC and to the work of the Conventions (the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) and the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC). In particular, DIVERSITAS contributed to the development of the 4th Global Biodiversity Outlook (GBO-4), and to the CBD work on indicators and monitoring and on Access and Benefit-Sharing (ABS). As a result, two ABS documents were published: 1) Implementing Access &amp; Benefit-Sharing &amp; Ensuring Academic Non-Commercial Research for the Conservation &amp; Sustainable Use of Biodiversity and 2) Access and Benefit-Sharing in Latin America and the Caribbean: A science-policy dialogue for academic research. Overall, over 70 publications were produced as a result of DIVERSITAS activities in 2013-2014.        Last Modified: 12/16/2016       Submitted by: Deliang Chen]]></POR_COPY_TXT>
